{{LaVeyan Satanism box}} 

'''Greater and lesser magic''' (known also as '''high and low magic''' or collectively '''Satanic magic''') is a system of magic within [[LaVeyan Satanism]]. Greater magic is a form of [[ritual]] practice and is meant as [[psychodramatic]] [[catharsis]] to focus one's emotional energy for a specific purpose.  Lesser magic is the practice of [[Psychological manipulation|manipulation]] by means of [[applied psychology]] and [[glamour (presentation)|glamour]] (or [[Deception|"wile and guile"]]) to bend an individual or situation to one's will.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Command to Look: A Master Photographer's Method for Controlling the Human Gaze |first1=William |last1=Mortensen |first2=George |last2=Dunham |year=2014 |page=203}}</ref>

==Theory and definition==

Outlined in ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey defined magic as "the change in situations or events in accordance with one's will, which would, using normally accepted methods, be unchangeable."{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1pp=288&ndash;289|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2p=95|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=96}} This definition incorporates two broadly distinguished kinds of magic: ''greater'' and ''lesser''.{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2012|1pp=95&ndash;96|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=97}} According to LaVey, one of the goals of ritual magic is "to isolate the otherwise dissipated adrenal and other emotionally induced energy, and to convert it into a dynamically transmittable force."{{sfn|The Command to Look: A Master Photographer's Method for Controlling the Human Gaze|George Dunham|2014|p=221}} LaVey defined lesser magic as "wile and guile obtained through various devices and contrived situations, which when utilized, can create change in accordance with one's will."{{sfn|Witchcraft and Magic in Europe, Volume 6: The Twentieth Century|Blecourt, Hutton, Fontaine|1999|page=91}} Within this system of magic, the terms [[warlock]] and [[witch]] are most commonly used by, and to refer to, male and female practitioners, respectively.

LaVey espoused the view that there was an objective reality to magic, and that it relied upon natural forces that were yet to be discovered by science.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} Rather than characterising these as [[supernatural]], LaVey expressed the view that they were part of the natural world.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|pp=3–4}} He believed that the successful use of magic involved the magician manipulating these natural forces using the force of their own willpower.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} LaVey also wrote of "the balance factor", insisting that any magical aims should be realistic.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=98}} LaVey refused any division between [[black magic]] and [[white magic]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=Dyrendal|2y=2012|2p=377}} attributing this dichotomy purely to the "smug hypocrisy and self-deceit" of those who called themselves "white magicians".{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=377}} Such [[Gray magic|neutrality]] correlates with LaVey's philosophical view of an impersonal, and therefore amoral, universe.<ref name="LaVey 1969">{{cite book |last=LaVey |first=Anton |authorlink=Anton LaVey |title= The Satanic Bible |year=1969 |publisher=Avon }}</ref> 

